  "prompt": "When you look at yourself in the mirror, is the reality of what other people see greater or worse than what you see?",
  "response": "Perception of oneself in the mirror is a complex and subjective experience that can differ greatly from how others perceive you. There are a few factors to consider:\n\n1. **Self-Criticism:** You may be more critical or attentive to your own perceived flaws, leading to a harsher judgment of your appearance than what others might see. People tend to focus on their own flaws more intensely than others do.\n\n2. **Familiarity:** You are extremely familiar with your own face, leading you to notice subtle changes or details that others might overlook. This familiarity can sometimes amplify perceived imperfections but can also create a sense of comfort.\n\n3. **Psychological State:** Your mood and self-esteem can influence how you see yourself. When feeling confident, you may perceive yourself more positively, whereas a bad day can lead to a more negative self-assessment.\n\n4. **Mirror Image:** Remember that a mirror shows a reversed image, which may look slightly different from how you appear to others. Photos and videos might offer a more accurate representation in that sense.\n\n5. **Others' Perspectives:** People have different tastes and perceptions; what you consider a flaw might be completely unnoticed or even valued by someone else.\n\nUltimately, the reality of what others see is subjective and influenced by their own perceptions and biases. Comparing your self-view to what others see isn\u2019t straightforward and involves considering the aforementioned factors.",
